  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a real, tangible barrier that I've observed in my own time as a retired educator and community member in Washington, DC. When I recall the stories of young students who, because they're the only ones in their class with a certain background, start to doubt their abilities before even starting a test, it becomes clear that this phenomenon is deeply rooted in our educational system. I've seen it firsthand: a girl from a low-income neighborhood who's brilliant but hesitates to raise her hand because she worries she'll be labeled 'not smart enough' for a math problem. Stereotype threat is the psychological burden that comes from knowing one's group is stereotyped as less capable in a particular domain. It's not just about the stereotype itself but the anxiety that it generates, which can impair performance. As someone who has lived through this in my own youth—my father was a teacher and I remember his frustration when students assumed I wasn't cut out for science because I was the son of a laborer—it's a problem that needs addressing. The answer isn't just to change the stereotypes but to create environments where students feel safe to explore without fear of judgment. For example, when I volunteer at local schools, I make an effort to highlight diverse role models in STEM who come from similar backgrounds to the students. This helps dismantle the fear and builds confidence. We must address this by integrating inclusive practices into curricula and fostering a culture where everyone feels valued, not just the ones who fit the 'ideal' mold. It's a slow process, but it's necessary for the future of our community.",
